    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so when you say it's a \"byproduct\" that's just sitting there, does it actually cause any physical damage to the muscle fibers or just that burning feeling? like, what exactly is happening at the cellular level to cause that discomfort?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The lactic acid buildup itself doesn't directly cause physical damage to muscle fibers, but the accumulation of lactic acid can lead to a phenomenon called \"metabolic fatigue.\" At the cellular level, the high concentration of lactic acid disrupts the normal functioning of the muscle fibers, particularly the myofibrils and sarcoplasmic reticulum. This disruption leads to an accumulation of calcium ions, which can cause muscle fibers to contract abnormally and lead to the characteristic burning or soreness sensation. Think of it like a misfired alarm system in the muscle, signaling that something's amiss.",
      "source": "target",
